stickerText: We wanted to share with you 3 traditional Inuit items that you might not know of 🤔
You might know this one already, a women’s knife called Ulu

It’s sharp and the shape makes it very easy to cut
This is a Qulliq, a traditional oil lamp that provides light and warmth🔥

And finally Kamik, these are traditional Inuit boots that are made out of seal or caribou skin
it’s very good for cold weather and it’s waterproof😊

stickerText: If you don't believe in mermaids, this is the story of Sedna. The Goddess of the sea
The Inuit legend says that Sedna was a young beautiful woman. Living with her parents up north
And her father absolutely wanted her to marry. She refused every man until one promised her a great life
He said he was a great hunter and that he would provide
They move far away together, but turned out he was an imposter. He was a shapeshifter. He wasn't a man, he was a bird. He lied and made her starve
Sedna's father comes to the rescue and kills the bird man. They left by Kayak
The bird man's friends came and flapped their wings so hard to shake their boat. Sedna fell over the boat and was holding on for her life
The father took out his traditional knife called "Ulu". Cut all of her fingers one by one
Sedna sank into the ocean, became a mermaid and each of her fingers became a sea animal that we now have today

stickerText:
This video has been circulating everywhere.
And as a throat singer myself, ive been recieveing a lot of comments asking and saying
Well it's funny! Why can't we laugh if you're laughing in your throat singing videos???
And yes, we laugh every single time. But we are not making fun of our throat songs. Thats the difference
We laugh because we have such a great bond and we are having fun throat singing because its a game.
There's a difference between having fun and mocking... and i get that a lot in my comment section
So i will keep fighting and keep throat singing on my tiktok. Raise awareness and bring positivity in throat singing☀️

stickerText: Growing up, I've been asked many questions about this scar...
If you're Indigenous, then you know what this is
Many Indigenous babies were vaccinated against TB (Tuberculosis)
It's very infectious, and it's a bacteria that affects your lungs, brain, spine or kidney
Mostly lungs but it can spread to other organs
And many Inuit received this vaccine because Northern communities were at higher risk of getting infected
Back in 1950's, many Inuit children were sent down south to be treated and sometimes it would take years
With some children that never made it back home
